"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">25</A>
The text translates roughly Nipperdey's proposal: <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Tum permissu <SPAN CLASS="emend">&#60;imperatoris deducitur a Stertinio&#62;</SPAN>, progressusque</SPAN> <I>e.q.s.</I>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note26" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2A*.html#ref26
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">26</A>
The leading centurion of the sixty in a legion was the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">primipilus</SPAN> — the first centurion of the first maniple of the first cohort. On the completion of his service he frequently received equestrian rank, and was employed in positions of very considerable responsibility. Here Aemilius (probably the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">vir militaris</SPAN> of
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/4C*.html#42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.42</A>) acts as <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">praefectus equitum</SPAN>. An inscription, which should apparently be referred to him, runs: <SPAN CLASS="lapis">Paulo Aemilio, D. f., primo pilo, bis praefecto equitum, tribuno cohortis IIII praetoriae</SPAN> (<SPAN CLASS="small"><SPAN CLASS="small">CIL</SPAN></SPAN> <SPAN CLASS="small">X</SPAN>.3881).


