<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note35" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2A*.html#ref35
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">35</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">salutatio imperatoria</SPAN>, by which, under the republic, the victorious general was acclaimed as <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">imperator</SPAN> by his troops, and crowned with bays, was now, with the triumph, a prerogative of the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">princeps</SPAN>: a fact symbolized by the laurel planted before the palace. See below,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/3D*.html#74
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.74</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note36" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2A*.html#ref36
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">36</A>
In order to complete the suppression of the revolt mentioned at the close of
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2A*.html#8
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. 8</A>: the same doubt as to the reading exists, of course, here.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note37" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2A*.html#ref37
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">37</A>
The period would be July. The summer, like the other seasons, was divided into three months: in the first, it was


<A ID="p415x"></A><SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">nova</SPAN>; in the second, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">adulta</SPAN>; in the third, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">praeceps</SPAN> (Servius on <I>Georg.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.43)<!--</A>SERVIUS:GEORGICS-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note38" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2A*.html#ref38
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">38</A>
The underlying theory is that the sodden lands and the rivers form the clouds by evaporation; the clouds, in their turn, give rise to the wind (Sen. <I>Q. N.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">V</SPAN>.5; <I>ib.</I> 13).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note39" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2A*.html#ref39
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">39</A>
Between the Weser and Holland: the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">saxa abrupta</SPAN>, like the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Scopuli</SPAN> of the next chapter, can be only a mistaken literary embellishment.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note40" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2A*.html#ref40
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">40</A>
The open ocean as opposed to land-locked seas.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note41" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2A*.html#ref41
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">41</A>
Presumably off the coast of Schleswig.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note42" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2A*.html#ref42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">42</A>
The influence of Pedo Albinovanus' poem (see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/1D*.html#note14
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
p345, n.</A>) has been plausibly suspected in more places than one of this narrative.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note43" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Annals/2A*.html#ref43
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">43</A>
The verdict of history upon these campaigns must, however, coincide with that of Tiberius.



